## Chapter 6 Summary: Operators

This chapter covered the full set of C++ operators you'll use constantly, along with several traps that catch newcomers.

**Precedence and associativity** determine evaluation order when multiple operators appear in one expression. When in doubt, use parentheses — they cost nothing and remove ambiguity.

**Arithmetic operators** (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`, `%`) behave mostly as expected, but integer division truncates toward zero. The remainder operator `%` works only on integers and takes the sign of the left operand in C++.

**Exponentiation** has no built-in operator; use `std::pow` from `<cmath>`. Be aware it works with `double`, so results fed back into integer math need an explicit cast.

**Increment/decrement** (`++`/`--`) come in prefix and postfix forms. Prefix modifies the value *before* it is used in an expression; postfix modifies it *after*. Prefer prefix when the old value isn't needed. Mixing these operators with other uses of the same variable in one expression causes undefined behavior.

**The comma operator** evaluates both operands left-to-right and returns the right one. It is rarely useful outside specific contexts and is best avoided elsewhere to keep code readable.

**The conditional operator** `?:` is a compact if-else for expressions. It requires both branches to produce compatible types and works well inside initializers or output expressions where a full `if` statement would be awkward.

**Relational operators** (`<`, `>`, `<=`, `>=`, `==`, `!=`) work correctly for integers but are unreliable for floating-point values due to rounding. Compare floating-point numbers with a scaled epsilon check — `std::abs(a - b) <= eps * std::max(1.0, std::max(std::abs(a), std::abs(b)))` — rather than `==`. The simpler `std::abs(a - b) < epsilon` works for small values but breaks down for large magnitudes.

**Logical operators** (`&&`, `||`, `!`) short-circuit: `&&` stops at the first `false`, `||` stops at the first `true`. This matters when operands have side effects.

```cpp
#include <cmath>
#include <iostream>

bool approx_equal(double a, double b, double eps = 1e-9) {
    return std::abs(a - b) <= eps * std::max(1.0, std::max(std::abs(a), std::abs(b)));
}

int main() {
    double a = 0.1 + 0.2;
    double b = 0.3;

    std::cout << std::boolalpha;
    std::cout << "0.1 + 0.2 == 0.3 ? " << (a == b) << '\n';
    std::cout << "approx_equal?      " << approx_equal(a, b) << '\n';

    int score = 87;
    char grade = (score >= 90) ? 'A' : (score >= 80) ? 'B' : 'C';
    std::cout << "Grade: " << grade << '\n';
}
```

This example combines the floating-point comparison technique (using the scaled epsilon from lesson 6.7), the conditional operator chained for a grade lookup, and `std::cout` — all patterns from this chapter applied together.

